<h2>Solar Incentives in Spokane</h2>

<p>Spokane residents benefit from multiple layers of solar incentives that significantly reduce the upfront cost of installation. The federal Investment Tax Credit (ITC) provides a 30% tax credit on the total system cost through 2032, then decreases to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. Washington State offers additional benefits including no state sales tax on solar equipment purchases and property tax exemptions for the added home value from solar installations. Avista provides net metering credits at retail rates, meaning excess solar production is credited at the full 9.8¬¢/kWh rate. Additionally, Washington's Renewable Energy System Incentive Program historically provided production incentives, and while the program has ended for new applications, existing participants continue to receive benefits. Local utility rebates and financing programs may also be available through Avista's energy efficiency initiatives.</p>

<h2>Best Solar Companies in Spokane</h2>

<p>When selecting a solar installer in Spokane, prioritize companies with extensive cold-climate experience and proper Washington state licensing. Look for contractors who hold current Washington State Department of Labor and Industries electrical contractor licenses and NABCEP (North American Board of Certified Energy Practitioners) certifications. Experienced Spokane installers understand the importance of proper snow load calculations, optimal tilt angles for winter sun exposure, and weatherproofing techniques essential for Pacific Northwest conditions. Quality installers should provide comprehensive warranties covering equipment (typically 20-25 years for panels, 10-15 years for inverters) and workmanship (minimum 5-10 years). Request multiple quotes, verify insurance coverage, check Better Business Bureau ratings, and ask for local references from recent installations. Top-tier companies will conduct thorough site assessments, provide detailed production estimates specific to Spokane's climate, and handle all permitting and utility interconnection paperwork with Avista.</p>

